definition.p:
We can represent a matrix in the following way:



    A = \begin{bmatrix}
    a_{11} & a_{12} & \dots & a_{1n} \\
    a_{21} & a_{22} & \dots & a_{2n} \\
    \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
    a_{m1} & a_{m2} & \dots & a_{mn} \\
    \end{bmatrix} 



    The ith row is \begin{bmatrix}
    a_{i1} & a_{i2} & \dots & a_{in} \\
    \end{bmatrix} , a 1\times n row matrix.



    The jth column is \begin{bmatrix}
    a_{1j} \\ a_{2j} \\ \vdots \\ a_{mj} \\
    \end{bmatrix} , an m\times 1 column matrix.



    The ijth term of the matrix is denoted a_{ij}



    We will often write A = \begin{bmatrix} a_{ij} \end{bmatrix}  and give a rule for a_{ij} in order to conserve space when relevant.

Let A = \begin{bmatrix} a_{ij} \end{bmatrix} and B = \begin{bmatrix} b_{ij} \end{bmatrix} be two m\times n matrices. We define their sum by:
 A + B = \begin{bmatrix} a_{ij} + b_{ij} \end{bmatrix} 
That is, we add the corresponding entries together. The result is also an m\times n matrix.

statement.p:
... and if we try to multiply something that doesn't work, we will get an error:


    A = matrix([[3, 1, 2], [5,2, 1], [1, 1, 0]]);
    B = matrix([[1, 2, 0], [4,0, 1]]);
    A*B


DON'T PANIC! We'll look through the error and see information that will help us understand.
